'''Dignified Mobile Toilets (DMT)''' is a [[portable toilets|mobile]] [[public toilet]] system created in 1992 by Isaac Durojaiye (a.k.a. Otunba Gaddafi).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://millionaire.ng/otunba-ghadafi-how-one-man-turned-shit-into-big-business/|website=Millionaire|date=July 15, 2017|title=OTUNBA GHADAFI: How one man turned shit into big business|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ng/books?id=24nCAAAAIAAJ&q=dmt+toilets+lagos&dq=dmt+toilets+lagos&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixj6LEtePaAhVJ6KQKHdVZDroQ6AEIODAF|title=Even here, even now: inspiring stories, lessons, and smart advice from 12 leading entrepreneurs and visionaries in Nigeria|author=Adeniyi Adekunle|author2=Olakunle Kasumu|publisher=AwakeAfrica|year=2005|ISBN=9789780673345}}</ref> Known by the slogan "''shit business is serious business!''";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thenationonlineng.net/toilets/|date=May 5, 2016|author=Kofoworola Bello Issue|title=Toilets!|publisher=The Nation|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> it was the first in Nigeria, initially conceived as a solution to providing human comfort during outdoor parties, events and other social gatherings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenigerianvoice.com/news/80892/why-i-went-into-toilet-business-durojaiye.html|website=The Nigerian Voice|title=WHY I WENT INTO TOILET BUSINESS- DUROJAIYE|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> The mobile toilets are manufactured in Nigeria, rented or sold in Nigeria and other West African countries. After its inception, DMT aimed at reducing the public toilets deficit and improving sanitation particularly among residents in city of Lagos.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W5rLZfjy2Pg|website=YouTube|title=Mobile toilets big business in Nigeria|publisher=CNN|year=2010|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/daily/index.php/feature/11068-toilets-in-nigeria-iii-thinking-of-bio-gas|publisher=Daily Trust|title=Toilets in Nigeria (III)Thinking of bio gas|date=November 28, 2013|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6133556.stm|title=Answering the call of nature in Lagos|date= November 16, 2006|website=BBC|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ng/books?id=nCElDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=dignified+mobile+toilets+dmt+lagos&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiB0MfcyeHaAhUsDMAKHXjdAqIQ6AEIKDAB#v=onepage&q=dignified%20mobile%20toilets%20dmt%20lagos&f=false|title=Social Entrepreneurship: Managing the Creation of Social Value|author=Constant iiiiBeugré|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2016|ISBN= 9781136655869|page=52|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneonlineng.com/lucrative-st-individual-profit-lack-toilets/|publisher=Tribune|title=Lucrative s**t! How some individual profit from lack of toilets|date=November 20, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> DMT now plans to recycle human waste to [[biogas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://challenges.openideo.com/challenge/how-can-we-improve-sanitation-and-better-manage-human-waste-in-low-income-urban-communities/inspiration/-shit-is-serious-business-2013-wagon-toilets|title="Shit is Serious Business" – Wagon Toilets|author=Meana Kadri|website=Openideo|accessdate=April 30, 2017|date=December 3, 2010}}</ref>
